1. API signature
String.prototype.codePointAt(position) -> number | undefined

2. Behavior and return value
- Returns the code point value (integer) at the given position in the string. If position is out of range, returns undefined.
- When position points to a high surrogate followed by a low surrogate, returns the combined code point (single Unicode scalar value).

3. Parameters and types
- position: integer index (0-based) into the string's UTF-16 code units. Non-integer values are converted to integer via ToInteger.
- Return: non-negative integer representing the Unicode code point, or undefined if out of bounds.

4. Example iteration considerations (surrogate pairs)
- To iterate over code points, either use for...of which yields valid code point strings, or use codePointAt with manual index advancement: if codePointAt(i) > 0xFFFF then advance i by 2 code units, else by 1.

5. Implementation details for JS
- Use x.codePointAt(i) to obtain numeric code point. Avoid using charCodeAt for full-code-point correctness because charCodeAt returns single 16-bit unit.

6. Supplementary notes
- codePointAt does not normalize or validate beyond surrogate pairing; it returns numeric values including those > 0xFFFF when pairs present.

